{"title_page": "John Thomson (Australian politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = John Thomson\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = John Thomson (Australian politician).jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]]\n| parliament = Australian\n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Henry Lee (Australian politician)|Henry Lee]]\n| successor = [[Earle Page]]\n| term_start = 12 December 1906\n| term_end = 13 December 1919\n| birth_date = 1862\n| birth_place = [[Taree, New South Wales]]\n| death_date = {{BirthDeathAge| |1862| | |1934|7|14|yes}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Australia]]n\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Protectionist Party|Protectionist]] (1906&ndash;09) <br> [[Commonwealth Liberal Party|Liberal]] (1909&ndash;17) <br> [[Nationalist Party of Australia|Nationalist]] (1917&ndash;19)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Shopkeeper, grazier\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Thomson''' (1862 &ndash; 14 July 1934) was an [[Australia]]n politician. He was a [[Progressive Party (1901)|Progressive Party]] member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] from 1901 to 1904, representing the [[Electoral district of Manning|Manning]] electorate. He was then a member of the [[Australian House of Representatives]] from 1906 to 1919, representing [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]] for the [[Protectionist Party]] and its successors the [[Commonwealth Liberal Party]] and [[Nationalist Party (Australia)|Nationalist Party]].\n\nThomson was born at Woolla (now [[Kolodong, New South Wales|Kolodong]]), near [[Taree, New South Wales|Taree]], where his father was the local teacher. He was educated at Taree before entering his family's Taree general store business, taking over as manager following the death of his father in 1884. He was an alderman of the [[Municipality of Taree]] and its mayor from 1896 to 1901, president of the Manning River Agricultural & Horticultural Society and president of the Manning River District Hospital board.<ref name=namobit>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article217860874 |title=MR. JOHN THOMSON. |newspaper=[[The Nambucca and Bellinger News]] |volume=29 |issue=1473 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=20 July 1934 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=dungogobit>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141466207 |title=OBITUARY. |newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=24 July 1934 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref name=mrtobit>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article171836985 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Manning River Times And Advocate For The Northern Coast Districts Of New South Wales]] |volume=66 |issue=8353 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=18 July 1934 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nHe was elected to the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] at the [[1901 New South Wales state election|1901 state election]] in the [[Electoral district of Manning|Manning]] electorate, but was defeated in 1904 when Manning was abolished and he attempted to contest the [[Electoral district of Gloucester|Gloucester]] seat.<ref name=namobit />\n\nIn 1906, Thomson was elected to the [[Australian House of Representatives]] as a [[Protectionist Party|Protectionist]], defeating [[Henry Lee (Australian politician)|Henry Lee]] of the [[Anti-Socialist Party]] for the seat of [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]]. In 1909 he became a member of the [[Commonwealth Liberal Party]], the result of a fusion between the Protectionists and the Anti-Socialists. In 1911, he was part of the parliamentary party that visited [[England]] as guests for the [[Coronation of George V and Mary]]. He was a member of the Royal Commission on the Fruit Industry from 1912 to 1914, temporary chairman of committees from 1913 to 1917, a member of the Joint Committee on Public Accounts from 1914 to 1919 and its chairman from 1917. In 1917, the Commonwealth Liberal Party merged into the new [[Nationalist Party (Australia)|Nationalist Party]], and Thomson was Ministerial Whip from 1917 to 1919. He was defeated in 1920 by future [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Earle Page]], who contested for the Farmers and Settlers Association.<ref name=namobit /> He was briefly touted as a possible candidate for a state seat in the mid-1920s, but this did not occur.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article174431886 |title=AGAIN JOHN THOMSON. |newspaper=[[The Macleay Chronicle]] |issue=2504 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 December 1926 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nFollowing his parliamentary defeat, Thomson briefly resided in [[Melbourne]] before returning to his family business, serving as chairman of directors of what was now incorporated as Thomsons Ltd., a role he held until his death. He also purchased a grazing and dairying property at [[Mount George, New South Wales|Mount George]], and increasingly retired there apart from his board duties in his later years. He died at Mount George in 1934 and was buried at the Dawson River Cemetery at [[Cundletown, New South Wales|Cundletown]].<ref name=namobit /><ref name=dungogobit /><ref name=mrtobit />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nsw-la}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Henry Young|James Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Manning|Manning]] | years=1901\u20131904}}\n{{s-non|reason=Abolished}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]] | before=[[Henry Lee (Australian politician)|Henry Lee]]| after=[[Earle Page]]| years=1906&ndash;1919}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomson, John}}\n[[Category:Protectionist Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Liberal Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Nationalist Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Cowper]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = John Thomson\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = John Thomson (Australian politician).jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]]\n| parliament = Australian\n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Henry Lee (Australian politician)|Henry Lee]]\n| successor = [[Earle Page]]\n| term_start = 12 December 1906\n| term_end = 13 December 1919\n| birth_date = 1862\n| birth_place = [[Taree, New South Wales]]\n| death_date = {{BirthDeathAge| |1862| | |1934|7|14|yes}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Australia]]n\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Protectionist Party|Protectionist]] (1906&ndash;09) <br> [[Commonwealth Liberal Party|Liberal]] (1909&ndash;17) <br> [[Nationalist Party of Australia|Nationalist]] (1917&ndash;19)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Shopkeeper, grazier\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Thomson''' (1862 &ndash; 14 July 1934) was an [[Australia]]n politician. He was a [[Progressive Party (1901)|Progressive Party]] member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] from 1901 to 1904, representing the [[Electoral district of Manning|Manning]] electorate. He was then a member of the [[Australian House of Representatives]] from 1906 to 1919, representing [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]] for the [[Protectionist Party]] and its successors the [[Commonwealth Liberal Party]] and [[Nationalist Party (Australia)|Nationalist Party]].\n\nThomson was born at Woolla (now [[Kolodong, New South Wales|Kolodong]]), near [[Taree, New South Wales|Taree]], where his father was the local teacher. He was educated at Taree before entering his family's Taree general store business, taking over as manager following the death of his father in 1884. He was an alderman of the [[Municipality of Taree]] and its mayor from 1896 to 1901, president of the Manning River Agricultural & Horticultural Society and president of the Manning River District Hospital board.<ref name=namobit>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article217860874 |title=MR. JOHN THOMSON. |newspaper=[[Nambucca and Bellinger News]] |volume=29 |issue=1473 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=20 July 1934 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=dungogobit>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141466207 |title=OBITUARY. |newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=24 July 1934 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref name=mrtobit>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article171836985 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Manning River Times And Advocate For The Northern Coast Districts Of New South Wales]] |volume=66 |issue=8353 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=18 July 1934 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nHe was elected to the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] at the [[1901 New South Wales state election|1901 state election]] in the [[Electoral district of Manning|Manning]] electorate, but was defeated in 1904 when Manning was abolished and he attempted to contest the [[Electoral district of Gloucester|Gloucester]] seat.<ref name=namobit />\n\nIn 1906, Thomson was elected to the [[Australian House of Representatives]] as a [[Protectionist Party|Protectionist]], defeating [[Henry Lee (Australian politician)|Henry Lee]] of the [[Anti-Socialist Party]] for the seat of [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]]. In 1909 he became a member of the [[Commonwealth Liberal Party]], the result of a fusion between the Protectionists and the Anti-Socialists. In 1911, he was part of the parliamentary party that visited [[England]] as guests for the [[Coronation of George V and Mary]]. He was a member of the Royal Commission on the Fruit Industry from 1912 to 1914, temporary chairman of committees from 1913 to 1917, a member of the Joint Committee on Public Accounts from 1914 to 1919 and its chairman from 1917. In 1917, the Commonwealth Liberal Party merged into the new [[Nationalist Party (Australia)|Nationalist Party]], and Thomson was Ministerial Whip from 1917 to 1919. He was defeated in 1920 by future [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Earle Page]], who contested for the Farmers and Settlers Association.<ref name=namobit /> He was briefly touted as a possible candidate for a state seat in the mid-1920s, but this did not occur.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article174431886 |title=AGAIN JOHN THOMSON. |newspaper=[[The Macleay Chronicle]] |issue=2504 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 December 1926 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nFollowing his parliamentary defeat, Thomson briefly resided in [[Melbourne]] before returning to his family business, serving as chairman of directors of what was now incorporated as Thomsons Ltd., a role he held until his death. He also purchased a grazing and dairying property at [[Mount George, New South Wales|Mount George]], and increasingly retired there apart from his board duties in his later years. He died at Mount George in 1934 and was buried at the Dawson River Cemetery at [[Cundletown, New South Wales|Cundletown]].<ref name=namobit /><ref name=dungogobit /><ref name=mrtobit />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nsw-la}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Henry Young|James Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of Manning|Manning]] | years=1901\u20131904}}\n{{s-non|reason=Abolished}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Division of Cowper|Cowper]] | before=[[Henry Lee (Australian politician)|Henry Lee]]| after=[[Earle Page]]| years=1906&ndash;1919}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomson, John}}\n[[Category:Protectionist Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Liberal Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Nationalist Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Cowper]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "redirect bypass fromNambucca and Bellinger NewstoThe Nambucca and Bellinger Newsusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Thomson_(Australian_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Se a vida \u00e9 (That's the Way Life Is)", "text_new": "{{short description|1996 single by Pet Shop Boys}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Se a vida \u00e9 (That's the Way Life Is)\n| cover      = Pet_Shop_Boys_-_SeAVidaE.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Pet Shop Boys]]\n| album      = [[Bilingual (album)|Bilingual]]\n| A-side     = \"To Step Aside\" <small>(US)</small>\n| B-side     = \"Betrayed\", \"How I Learned to Hate Rock & Roll\"\n| released   = {{start date|1996|8|12|df=yes}} (UK) <br>{{start date|1997|4|1|df=yes}} (US)\n| format     = [[7-inch single|7\"]], [[12-inch single|12\"]], [[CD single|CD]] [[Cassette Single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Latin pop]], [[dance-pop]], [[Ax\u00e9 (music)|Ax\u00e9]]\n| length     = 4:02\n| label      = [[Parlophone Records|Parlophone]] \u2013 <small>R 6443</small> (UK)<br>[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] \u2013 <small>85430</small> (US)\n| writer     = Nego Do Barbalho / Wellington Epiderme Negra / Ademario / [[Neil Tennant]] / [[Chris Lowe]]\n| producer   = Pet Shop Boys, Chris Porter\n| prev_title = [[Before (song)|Before]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Single-Bilingual]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\n\n\"'''Se a vida \u00e9 (That's the Way Life Is)'''\" is a [[Pet Shop Boys]] song that was released as a single on 12 August 1996, the second track to be lifted from the album ''[[Bilingual (album)|Bilingual]]'', which saw the duo take on a Latin influence as a reaction to the [[Britpop]] explosion that was prevalent at the time.\n\nThe single was one of the most widely played records on UK radio in 1996, and reached number eight in the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nIn the US, the single was released by [[Atlantic Records]] in April 1997 with \"To Step Aside\" as a double A-side. Thirteen mixes of the track were commissioned and spread over various formats, several of them promotional-only. The single did not chart in the States, but following its success in the UK it became a major success all over Europe. (Curiously, despite the [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] title, it was not a hit in [[Portugal]], nor in the other major [[Lusophone]] country, [[Brazil]].)\n\n==Music video==\nThe video for the single was shot at the [[Wet 'n Wild (United States)|Wet 'n Wild]] water theme park in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Florida]] and features the actress [[Eva Mendes]] in a small role as a teenager with her friends at the park. The video, directed by [[Bruce Weber (photographer)|Bruce Weber]], entered heavy rotation on [[MTV]] and [[VH1]] that summer.\n\n==Translation==\nThe correct English translation of \"Se a vida \u00e9\" from Portuguese is actually \"If Life Is...\". (\"That's the way life is\" would be \"\u00c9 assim que a vida \u00e9...\" or \"A vida \u00e9 assim\".) The other Portuguese lyric is \"Essa vida \u00e9...\" (\"This life is...\"), which sounds very similar to \"Se a vida \u00e9\".\n\n==Track listing==\n\n'''7\": Parlophone / RLH 6443 (UK)'''\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9 (That's the Way Life Is)\" \u2013 4:01\n# \"Before (Single Edit)\"\n\n'''CD: Parlophone / CDR 6443 (UK)'''\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9 (That's the Way Life Is)\" \u2013 4:01\n# \"Betrayed\" \u2013 5:18\n# \"How I Learned to Hate Rock 'n' Roll\" \u2013 4:40\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9\" (Pink Noise mix) \u2013 5:37\n\n'''CD: Parlophone / CDRS 6443 (UK)'''\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9\" (Mark Picchiottis Deep and Dark vocal) \u2013 7:58\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9\" (Mark Picchiottis Shelter dub) \u2013 8:40\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9\" (Deep Dish Liquid remix) \u2013 9:57\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9\" (Deep Dish dub) \u2013 11:45\n\n'''CD: Atlantic / 85430-2 (US)'''\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9 (That's the Way Life Is)\" (Album version) \u2013 4:01\n# \"Se a vida \u00e9\" (Mark Picchiotti's Deep and Dark vocal) \u2013 7:58\n# \"To Step Aside\" (album version) \u2013 3:48\n# \"To Step Aside\" (Ralphi's Disco vox) \u2013 9:07\n# \"The calm before the storm\" \u2013 2:45\n# \